textDisplay:
17:38 Regarding Mario Party online and people disconnecting, it just takes a little thinking put into the functionality to make that less of a problem. In the early WFC games (e.g., Star Fox Command), you need all four player slots to be occupied before a game will even start, it will search only for a limited time, and anyone disconnecting in the middle of a match will instantly end the whole room.
A smarter way to do it will be to either make allowances for having fewer than four people in a board, or make it where emptied player slots in the middle of a long-ish game can get occupied by CPUs (like the online UNO).

22:43 If it's like Twitch or most other EULAs/TOSs, they give themselves the right to terminate your service for any reason or no reason at all, extremely arbitrary definition over what they claim is "hate speech", etc. 25:15 Yep. They collected their $25,000 from him, they see no reason to continue providing him with 'free' service (watching what he had previously bought).
It's the same mentality behind them intentionally bricking iPhones repaired at shops other than Apple shops: They collected their money from the sale of the iPhone, they obviously won't get the repair money, thus they see no reason that person should get service anymore.
23:42 The difference here, though, is that natural disasters, legal "acts of God", etc. could take away the service. The issue here is that Apple is taking away access to what he bought.
25:35 I mean, I'd take losing my Apple account if that was my prize, lol.
textOriginal:

In the early WFC games (e.g., Star Fox Command), you need all four player slots to be occupied before a game will even start, it will search only for a limited time, and anyone disconnecting in the middle of a match will instantly end the whole room.
A smarter way to do it will be to either make allowances for having fewer than four people in a board, or make it where emptied player slots in the middle of a long-ish game can get occupied by CPUs (like the online UNO).

22:43 If it's like Twitch or most other EULAs/TOSs, they give themselves the right to terminate your service for any reason or no reason at all, extremely arbitrary definition over what they claim is "hate speech", etc. 25:15 Yep. They collected their $25,000 from him, they see no reason to continue providing him with 'free' service (watching what he had previously bought).
It's the same mentality behind them intentionally bricking iPhones repaired at shops other than Apple shops: They collected their money from the sale of the iPhone, they obviously won't get the repair money, thus they see no reason that person should get service anymore.
23:42 The difference here, though, is that natural disasters, legal "acts of God", etc. could take away the service. The issue here is that Apple is taking away access to what he bought.

textDisplay: 2020 was a  rough year for markets but Bitcoin has outperformed JPMorgan, Goldman Sachs, and the majority of top U.S. financial sector stocks. Historically, traditional market analysts and old school investors tend to look at Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies with a wary eye, and when crypto pundits attempt to make comparisons between the two these investors say it's an apples to oranges argument..... Take, for example, Warren Buffett, who many a time has said Bitcoin is nothing more than a Ponzi scheme as it does not produce anything and therefore has no value, According to these traditionalists, comparing Bitcoin to Apple, Tesla, or a bank stock like JPMorgan is irrational as the latter employ workers, produce products, and generate revenues and dividends which are distributed to shareholders.... Despite these arguments, a simple fact remains.>Bitcoin has had a strong year and the digital asset is outperforming financial stocks in 2021 due to a considerable increase in institutional demand, investors' belief in BTC's exponential growth potential, and its asymmetrical price action in the face of global economic uncertainty.. textDisplay:
No I haven’t located a PS5 yet.

I think the only real way to solve the problem is for Sony to prioritize selling bulk shipments to brick and mortar stores, and
then to have these brick and mortar stores
take orders in store only. It’s quite easy. Sony needs to abandon this model of releasing only 100 or so units worldwide at a time. Sony has to realize that only a jag off does that. How about only releasing when you have 5,000 units per state in the US? Every major city in a state would have at least 500 units, which means most Best Buy’s, Walmart’s, Target’s, etc. would likely have at least 50 units in their main city store. After that, The stores get in touch with local media a week before they begin selling a shipment. The news will report it and then people will line up like it’s Black Friday. One per person per day, in store only the entire way.

I believe this is the only way to screw scalpers and people with 50 relatives, while giving most people a chance to score a unit.
Either way, this screw up we have right now is already costing the gaming industry tens of millions in games not sold. Someone huddle up and do something. It isn’t that hard.

textDisplay:
I bought a shitload of loose Gameboy/Color/Advance games and a couple NES games from their online retro section about a year ago.

No repros and most everything was in good condition. The only thing I ever returned was a copy of NES Ducktales where one of the brackets that holds the PCB in place had broken off.
textOriginal:
I bought a shitload of loose Gameboy/Color/Advance games and a couple NES games from their online retro section about a year ago.

No repros and most everything was in good condition.  The only thing I ever returned was a copy of NES Ducktales where one of the brackets that holds the PCB in place had broken off.

textDisplay: Their buylist is a great resource for B&M stores around the US for current and older games. B&M retro stores can advertise that they pay more than Gamestop by just CSV downloading their list, uploading it to their system for just pennies more. Gamestop has been a great resource for all these other stores that actually have owners that care that they make money and take care of their customers while GS just continues to self-destruct.
textOriginal: Their buylist is a great resource for B&M stores around the US for current and older games. Gamestop has been a great resource for all these other stores that actually have owners that care that they make money and take care of their customers while GS just continues to self-destruct.

textDisplay: They would do their buy 2 get 1 free on Black Friday and every brick and mortar game store that I know of would wipe them out of anything good. They had the Gamestop reward membership that go them an extra 10-20% off of the games they actually had to pay for. They would have traded in all their junk games they don't sell on one of their get 50% more in trade in credit + 10-20% extra for being a reward member. There was an easy way for these retro game stores to completely play the system.
textOriginal: They would do their buy 2 get 1 free on Black Friday and every brick and mortar game store that I know of would wipe them out of anything good. textDisplay:
I clicked through just about every Vita game, and there wasn't a single one in stock. I did get incredibly lucky in that one of the stores here had two (cart only of course) in. And for reasonable prices.
I doubt that'll ever happen again.
textOriginal:
I clicked through just about _every_ Vita game, and there wasn't a single one in stock. I did get incredibly lucky in that one of the stores here had two (cart only of course) in. And for reasonable prices.
I doubt that'll ever happen again.

textDisplay:
I think if GameStop made this initiative a local store-by-store basis, where customers could see and try out the products first, and slowly rolled it out to each store, it might have worked better. I mean, you can't half-ass this market.

But they took this half-assed direction instead, and I am glad it's dead. I really didn't like the idea of GameStop taking these products out of the common space and having the opportunity to destroy them.

textDisplay: To be fair, GameStop did clean up their act after the initial year or so of accepting retro games, as I made three different all-retro purchases via the online store, and every single time they were all legit games, and I even bought one GBA game at an actual store & even that was legit. Sure, very few of them had a box, but I will admit that I was pleased with what GameStop was offering, especially when they were holding their sales (& most of what I got were Game Boy & GBA games, which are the most susceptible the being faked). That being said, it's obvious that once the pandemic hit GameStop pretty much stopped getting retro trade-ins, and have essentially stopped caring about that market ever since.

textDisplay:
The fact of the matter is, Gamestop has single-handedly brought the Vidyacaust upon the US retro game market, and nothing they could possibly try would undo even a fraction of that damage.

The saddest part is that didn't have to be like this. If Gamestop didn't buy out all of their direct competition, if they didn't gradually push all the retro stuff out to make space for the newer consoles, relegating it to non-chain mom'n'pop stores and Ebay scalpers, we might have been as well off as Japan with their ubiquitous retro scene, absurd selection and dirt-cheap prices (at least until gaijins started muscling in). But now your only option is to pay literal hundreds of dollars to turbojews from Ebay. :/

God help you if you're collecting for one of the meme consoles like the SNES, because it's only going to keep getting worse and worse. For some of these fucking games, even the repros (!) are starting to get pricy. I feel like I'm taking crazy pills.
textOriginal:
The fact of the matter is, Gamestop has single-handedly brought the Vidyacaust upon the US retro game market, and nothing they could possibly try would undo even a fraction of that damage. 

The saddest part is that didn't have to be like this. If Gamestop didn't buy out all of their direct competition, if they didn't gradually push all the retro stuff out to make space for the newer consoles, relegating it to non-chain mom'n'pop stores and Ebay scalpers, we might have been as well off as Japan with their ubiquitous retro scene, absurd selection and dirt-cheap prices (at least until gaijins started muscling in). But now your only option is to pay literal hundreds of dollars to turbojews from Ebay. :/

God help you if you're collecting for one of the meme consoles like the SNES, because it's only going to keep getting worse and worse. For some of these fucking games, even the repros (!) are starting to get pricy. I feel like I'm taking crazy pills.

so working off that number we start dividing down the 70trillion until we get the shares shorted number which would be the theoretical floor.... 70,000,000,000,000 / 2,500,000 = 28000000 (27million shares covered) the floor is 2.5mil or DTCC goes bankrupt. topkek. I am smooth brain ape and I have no idea where it could go I just like to smash my face on keyboard and press numbers.

textDisplay: It's funny that you mention not knowing anything about Reddit or WallStreetBets, because that community is where I first found out about you, and WallStreetBets in particular has probably been a significant contributing factor in your stock market channel going viral as quickly and explosively as it has. Apparently some folks over there discovered you during the early days of the initial GME short squeeze, and they've been posting links to your channel on the WSB subreddit ever since. I found my way here through one such link, in a post that spoke very highly of you and encouraged others to check out your channel. As one content creator to another, I think your ability to interpret and present the incredibly complex world of the stock market "in plain English" is one of the main reasons for your appeal to a younger audience on this channel, as is your all-around friendly and approachable personality. I for one am 35 years old and have found your discussions to be a fantastically useful resource. Meanwhile, most people I know who are around your age either never put any of their savings into the stock market, or lost everything they'd invested during the multitude of financial crises that have occurred over the past 20 or 30 years. It seems to me that this trend, in addition to how much easier it is to buy and sell stocks online nowadays compared to how tedious it was to call your stockbroker for every transaction back in the day, probably helps explain why so few people of your own generation have followed you here from your travel channel. Either way, you're doing great work—please keep it up! All the best to you, sir.

textDisplay: 2020 was a  rough year for markets but Bitcoin has outperformed JPMorgan, Goldman Sachs, and the majority of top U.S. financial sector stocks. Historically, traditional market analysts and old school investors tend to look at Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies with a wary eye, and when crypto pundits attempt to make comparisons between the two these investors say it's an apples to oranges argument..... Take, for example, Warren Buffett, who many a time has said Bitcoin is nothing more than a Ponzi scheme as it does not produce anything and therefore has no value, According to these traditionalists, comparing Bitcoin to Apple, Tesla, or a bank stock like JPMorgan is irrational as the latter employ workers, produce products, and generate revenues and dividends which are distributed to shareholders.... Despite these arguments, a simple fact remains.>Bitcoin has had a strong year and the digital asset is outperforming financial stocks in 2021 due to a considerable increase in institutional demand, investors' belief in BTC's exponential growth potential, and its asymmetrical price action in the face of global economic uncertainty.. So you can still make much better  profits by tradn.. textDisplay:
I bought a shitload of loose Gameboy/Color/Advance games and a couple NES games from their online retro section about a year ago.

No repros and most everything was in good condition. The only thing I ever returned was a copy of NES Ducktales where one of the brackets that holds the PCB in place had broken off.
textOriginal:
I bought a shitload of loose Gameboy/Color/Advance games and a couple NES games from their online retro section about a year ago.

No repros and most everything was in good condition.  The only thing I ever returned was a copy of NES Ducktales where one of the brackets that holds the PCB in place had broken off.

textDisplay: Their buylist is a great resource for B&M stores around the US for current and older games. B&M retro stores can advertise that they pay more than Gamestop by just CSV downloading their list, uploading it to their system for just pennies more. Gamestop has been a great resource for all these other stores that actually have owners that care that they make money and take care of their customers while GS just continues to self-destruct.
textOriginal: Their buylist is a great resource for B&M stores around the US for current and older games. textDisplay: They would do their buy 2 get 1 free on Black Friday and every brick and mortar game store that I know of would wipe them out of anything good. They had the Gamestop reward membership that go them an extra 10-20% off of the games they actually had to pay for. They would have traded in all their junk games they don't sell on one of their get 50% more in trade in credit + 10-20% extra for being a reward member. There was an easy way for these retro game stores to completely play the system.

I think if GameStop made this initiative a local store-by-store basis, where customers could see and try out the products first, and slowly rolled it out to each store, it might have worked better. I mean, you can't half-ass this market.

textDisplay: To be fair, GameStop did clean up their act after the initial year or so of accepting retro games, as I made three different all-retro purchases via the online store, and every single time they were all legit games, and I even bought one GBA game at an actual store & even that was legit. Sure, very few of them had a box, but I will admit that I was pleased with what GameStop was offering, especially when they were holding their sales (& most of what I got were Game Boy & GBA games, which are the most susceptible the being faked). That being said, it's obvious that once the pandemic hit GameStop pretty much stopped getting retro trade-ins, and have essentially stopped caring about that market ever since.

textDisplay:
The fact of the matter is, Gamestop has single-handedly brought the Vidyacaust upon the US retro game market, and nothing they could possibly try would undo even a fraction of that damage.

The saddest part is that didn't have to be like this. If Gamestop didn't buy out all of their direct competition, if they didn't gradually push all the retro stuff out to make space for the newer consoles, relegating it to non-chain mom'n'pop stores and Ebay scalpers, we might have been as well off as Japan with their ubiquitous retro scene, absurd selection and dirt-cheap prices (at least until gaijins started muscling in). But now your only option is to pay literal hundreds of dollars to turbojews from Ebay. :/

God help you if you're collecting for one of the meme consoles like the SNES, because it's only going to keep getting worse and worse. For some of these fucking games, even the repros (!) are starting to get pricy. I feel like I'm taking crazy pills.
textOriginal:
The fact of the matter is, Gamestop has single-handedly brought the Vidyacaust upon the US retro game market, and nothing they could possibly try would undo even a fraction of that damage. 

The saddest part is that didn't have to be like this. If Gamestop didn't buy out all of their direct competition, if they didn't gradually push all the retro stuff out to make space for the newer consoles, relegating it to non-chain mom'n'pop stores and Ebay scalpers, we might have been as well off as Japan with their ubiquitous retro scene, absurd selection and dirt-cheap prices (at least until gaijins started muscling in). But now your only option is to pay literal hundreds of dollars to turbojews from Ebay. :/

God help you if you're collecting for one of the meme consoles like the SNES, because it's only going to keep getting worse and worse. For some of these fucking games, even the repros (!) are starting to get pricy. I feel like I'm taking crazy pills.

textDisplay: It's funny that you mention not knowing anything about Reddit or WallStreetBets, because that community is where I first found out about you, and WallStreetBets in particular has probably been a significant contributing factor in your stock market channel going viral as quickly and explosively as it has. Apparently some folks over there discovered you during the early days of the initial GME short squeeze, and they've been posting links to your channel on the WSB subreddit ever since. I found my way here through one such link, in a post that spoke very highly of you and encouraged others to check out your channel. As one content creator to another, I think your ability to interpret and present the incredibly complex world of the stock market "in plain English" is one of the main reasons for your appeal to a younger audience on this channel, as is your all-around friendly and approachable personality. I for one am 35 years old and have found your discussions to be a fantastically useful resource. Meanwhile, most people I know who are around your age either never put any of their savings into the stock market, or lost everything they'd invested during the multitude of financial crises that have occurred over the past 20 or 30 years. It seems to me that this trend, in addition to how much easier it is to buy and sell stocks online nowadays compared to how tedious it was to call your stockbroker for every transaction back in the day, probably helps explain why so few people of your own generation have followed you here from your travel channel. Either way, you're doing great work—please keep it up! All the best to you, sir.

Der Aktieneinsatz muss Spielgeld sein, auf das man auch für eine Zeit verzichten kann.

textDisplay:
Mit AMC habe ich auch richtig Minus gemacht. Für 13,60€ 1000 Stück gekauft und mit viel Glück nach einem Kursrutsch auf ca. 6,00€ noch für 12,00€ verkauft. BB und Nokia hatte ich nicht.
Mit Gamestop habe ich mehrere 1000,00€ im Durchschnitt plus gemacht. Allerdings zu 90% mit Daytrading. Mir war das immer zu heiss, diese länger im Depot zu lassen. Ich hatte auch viele Adrenalinstösse dabei weil ich zu früh gekauft habe und der Kurs nochmal so richtig in den Keller gegangen ist. Aber zum Abend ging er wieder hoch. GME hatte öfter einen Peak am Tag, wo der Kurs extrem gefallen und gestiegen ist. In den besten Zeiten bis zu 100€ innerhalb einer Stunde.

Ich finde es gut, dass Du auf solide Werte setzt und ein bisschen zockst.
Außer mit GME habe ich schon gutes Geld verdient mit Eckart&Ziegler und Curevac.

Viel Glück weiterhin.

Wenn ich noch einen Wunsch äußern dürfte, dann wünsche ich mir ein kleines bisschen zügigeres Sprechen 😉.

Gruß Andreas

textDisplay:
So let's step back and look at whats been happening. January AMC on the verge of bankruptcy. Apes seen what was happening and essentially saved the company. The stock goes from nothing to 20x. Us apes basically tossed a sensu bean to Adam Aron. We HODL, we suffered, we grew. He planned.

What if the 500 million shareholders dilution was a ploy. The only way to repay the apes, was to provide them with their tendies. Baiting the HF, with the proposal of nearly doubling the available stock. No doubt to ruining the stock.

So what happenes next, the HF feed, shorting lowering the stock, but yet we held. Now the trap was set.

And just like that the HF were caught by the leg. 500mil off the table. They screamed, "look 43mil, they can still dilute". But we HODL, not all, but most of us did.

next we see, is the 43mil being able to put into the market at any time. Godzilla vs Kong breaking records. WE HODL.

The HF continued shorting, thinking if they could bleed us enough, we would fall. HODL.

but us Apes grew tired of HODL, we grew hungry, we feed. Growing our profoilo, BUY, HODL.

We brought to stock to it maximum. 100%. For days. So the HF hit us elsewhere, our crypto. What could we do. We HODL.

Now no vote at all, follow by what I imagine is a good to Kong size earnings call.

So here we are. Awaiting the next move. Is it the squeeze? Is the rumors of a secret share count true? Has pushing back the vote done anything in the interest of the shareholder?

But as I sit here, on a old recliner in my garage. I ponder. What of the 43mil. Could, in a squeeze, a company who previously stated these were ready to be placed in the market at anytime, do so? Would feeding a steady supply of shares slowly into the market cause the stock to rise well beyond the normal / GAMMA squeeze under such buying pressure? Maybe even forces circumstances?

We were Promised Tendies.

What if the 500 million shareholders dilution was a ploy. The only way to repay the apes, was to provide them with their tendies. Baiting the HF, with the proposal of nearly doubling the available stock. No doubt to ruining the stock.

So what happenes next, the HF feed, shorting lowering the stock, but yet we held. Now the trap was set. 

And just like that the HF were caught by the leg. 500mil off the table. They screamed, "look 43mil, they can still dilute". But we HODL, not all, but most of us did.

next we see, is the 43mil being able to put into the market at any time. Godzilla vs Kong breaking records. WE HODL. 

The HF continued shorting, thinking if they could bleed us enough, we would fall. HODL.

but us Apes grew tired of HODL, we grew hungry, we feed. Growing our profoilo, BUY, HODL. 

We brought to stock to it maximum. 100%. For days. So the HF hit us elsewhere, our crypto. What could we do. We HODL. 

Now no vote at all, follow by what I imagine is a good to Kong size earnings call.

So here we are. Awaiting the next move. Is it the squeeze? Is the rumors of a secret share count true? Has pushing back the vote done anything in the interest of the shareholder?

But as I sit here, on a old recliner in my garage. I ponder. What of the 43mil. Could, in a squeeze, a company who previously stated these were ready to be placed in the market at anytime, do so? textDisplay:
So let's step back and look at whats been happening. January AMC on the verge of bankruptcy. Apes seen what was happening and essentially saved the company. The stock goes from nothing to 20x. Us apes basically tossed a sensu bean to Adam Aron. We HODL, we suffered, we grew. He planned.

What if the 500 million shareholders dilution was a ploy. The only way to repay the apes, was to provide them with their tendies. Baiting the HF, with the proposal of nearly doubling the available stock. No doubt to ruining the stock.

So what happenes next, the HF feed, shorting lowering the stock, but yet we held. Now the trap was set.

And just like that the HF were caught by the leg. 500mil off the table. They screamed, "look 43mil, they can still dilute". But we HODL, not all, but most of us did.

next we see, is the 43mil being able to put into the market at any time. Godzilla vs Kong breaking records. WE HODL.

The HF continued shorting, thinking if they could bleed us enough, we would fall. HODL.

but us Apes grew tired of HODL, we grew hungry, we feed. Growing our profoilo, BUY, HODL.

We brought to stock to it maximum. 100%. For days. So the HF hit us elsewhere, our crypto. What could we do. We HODL.

Now no vote at all, follow by what I imagine is a good to Kong size earnings call.

So here we are. Awaiting the next move. Is it the squeeze? Is the rumors of a secret share count true? Has pushing back the vote done anything in the interest of the shareholder?

But as I sit here, on a old recliner in my garage. I ponder. What of the 43mil. Could, in a squeeze, a company who previously stated these were ready to be placed in the market at anytime, do so? Would feeding a steady supply of shares slowly into the market cause the stock to rise well beyond the normal / GAMMA squeeze under such buying pressure? Maybe even forces circumstances?

We were Promised Tendies.

textDisplay:
Lol, the Duck Tales game is a floppy disk, just older. It is called a 5.25 (5 1/4) floppy. They are 5.25” in size. Back then floppy disks were actually “floppy”, unlike the 3.5” hard cased floppy disks. There was even an 8” floppy before the 5.25”.

Also, games with books and “media”, like cd/dvd or even floppy disks, can actually be shipped media mail through USPS. Media mail is WAY cheaper for heavy items, like books.

LOL please put down the crack pipe I was all-in for the gme short squeeze but hearing you talk about GameStop as if it is a viable business that has any real future is frankly jaw-dropping.

You talked at length about many numbers in relation to GameStop except for the most important one which is profit which they don't have. It doesn't matter how high your sales numbers are if you lost money in the process.

What exactly do you think GameStop is going to be able to sell digitally more cheaply and efficiently than their competition?

It's very easy to increase your eCommerce numbers by very large percentage when you started with a very small amount to begin with. And I wouldn't be surprised if they are playing games with those numbers also I bet they are counting fulfilling PowerUp Rewards points Redemption as e-commerce LMAO.

And let's say hypothetically by some strange Miracle they could match competitors pricing and efficiency why would the same Gamers they have been taking advantage of for decades choose them instead of the competition that didn't do that to them?

Their brick-and-mortar customer experience was terrible the stores and employees smelled like feet and they were very aggressive and predatory the only reason they stayed in business for as long as they did was because they had a monopoly on being the pawnshop of video games.

GameStop's customers hate GameStop GameStop's employees hate GameStop if we hadn't gotten the opportunity to eat hedge fund managers lunch then no one would be talking about GameStop right now lol

Comparing GameStop to chewy isn't rational your pets have a set consumption rate that is very predictable having a company that will keep you stocked up appropriately reliably and save you hours of your life not having to reorder the same things over and over every month is value-added video game consumption is the exact opposite.

textDisplay:
Lol, the Duck Tales game is a floppy disk, just older. It is called a 5.25 (5 1/4) floppy. They are 5.25” in size. Back then floppy disks were actually “floppy”, unlike the 3.5” hard cased floppy disks. There was even an 8” floppy before the 5.25”.

Also, games with books and “media”, like cd/dvd or even floppy disks, can actually be shipped media mail through USPS. Media mail is WAY cheaper for heavy items, like books.

textDisplay: Overvalued stocks, especially this one is never a good. Even though their debt has been almost taken care of, their e-commerce push is too late as other sources (song, Microsoft, steam) provide online games already. So net income won’t hike to offset expenses to help EPS which won’t help P/E. When the bear market hits, these are the hardest hit stocks since that bubble is formed and because their financial backing isn’t there to hold it up to keep it afloat. Dotcom bubble of the 90’s is a prime example. P.S. most hedge funds portfolios are long positions, they often hedge using other positions in other asset classes more so to shorting positions.

textDisplay: Overvalued stocks, especially this one is never a good. Even though their debt has been almost taken care of, their e-commerce push is too late as other sources (song, Microsoft, steam) provide online games already. So net income won’t hike to offset expenses to help EPS which won’t help P/E. When the bear market hits, these are the hardest hit stocks since that bubble is formed and because their financial backing isn’t there to hold it up to keep it afloat. Dotcom bubble of the 90’s is a prime example. P.S. most hedge funds portfolios are long positions, they often hedge using other positions in other asset classes more so to shorting positions.

textDisplay:
Vlad Tenev is full of excuses. Robinhood made it easy for Average Joe to invest in the stock market, however it's been long-known that "all in on index funds" is the best way to make the most money with the lowest risk and effort required. I would like to know the percentage of Robinhood accounts that have lost money since they were opened. I imagine it's somewhere in the 90's.

At the same time Graham Stephan is encouraging viewers to open accounts on the new trading platform Public, which is effectively Robinhood. There's 100% some hypocrisy there, regardless of how pure Public's vision or intentions may be.

Just put it in index funds, people. I know it's boring. If you want excitement, fire up GTA V and gamble on the BAWSAQ.

textDisplay:
Whether Robinhood itself is dead remains to be seen, but /r/robinhood is certainly a lost cause at this point. Whoever their main mod is, I think CardinalNumber, just bans anyone that is even remotely critical of Robinhood. I suggested RH should do more to educate users on the risks of trading penny stocks, and that got me a permanent ban. I was banned from /r/the_donald for something similar. These people are sociopaths and have no business moderating subreddits. I shudder to think about how many people have to deal with them in the real world.

Oddly enough it just makes me subconsciously dislike Robinhood more, knowing that their subreddit is corrupt.

textDisplay:
As much as I respect Buffett and Munger as investors... I also think they are close-minded just like my grandparents are. I doubt that it is intentional, but has to do more with the fact that they were raised (and saw success) in a different era. It's like trying to explain to your grandparents why Bitcoin is more more valuable than Gold... or what the LGBTQIA+ community is and what they stand for...

I definitely agree that new investors can get themselves in trouble by day trading, but those millennial investors that take a little more time to research and educate themselves know that you are better off holding your positions and buying at the dips versus trying to time the market. Even Buffett and Munger tell us this...

I use Robinhood simply because I'm new to investing and have a little "play money" put into the market... the user interface is simple enough for me to understand. If I become a little more savvy, I might consider a different trading platform.

textDisplay:
It's important to distinguish what 'investing' is and what it isn't. For most smart people, investing is taking a portion of what you've paid yourself from your income (i.e. your savings) and then allocating that money in different ways, based on the time frame of when you expect to need it.

Here is what investing is not: Getting your direct deposit twice a month and then immediately yeeting 70% of it into Robinhood to buy more stonks that someone told you will go 'to the moon.'

High risk investing in the OTC may have a place in your portfolio, but it should be a small percentage compared to more traditional and diversified investments. If you are working and not maxing out your IRA each year, or you have debts, and yet still somehow find money to chuck into RH, then you are doing something very wrong lol.

textDisplay: The entire argument is off. We are using the word investing for trading. New people to investing should not be trading. They need to learn a lot more. Regardless of the push notifications they will lose their money. The system profiting off retail traders has been going on long before Robinhood was even thought of. Most institutions use data to bet against retail traders. Now these platforms just aren't making the commissions like they used to because Robinhood has forced many to go commission free. Each of these platforms though, still make money of retail traders through many steps. Robinhood just so happens to also be a terrible platform for trading and I agree this is on purpose. There is a reason Robinhood has insanely dumbed down charts. When you have a platform that encourages trading but then doesn't provide proper tools to do so that should be a red flag. But many of these people trading have no idea what they are looking at or what they should be looking for. They are being played and have no idea. For someone like myself that writes finance programs, I am pretty aware of the parameters that these functions use to determine buy and sell orders. The variables are time and risk but beyond the variables most algos use similar parameters to gauge a buy or sell. If you can't do that, you need to focus on investing and not trading or at least swings between 3mo-12mo. Then you need to understand moving averages and time frames. This is just the basics and investing can be even more complex but you are still better off as long as you don't buy stocks like HMNY thinking it is going to be the next big thing because you aren't aware of how terrible the business model is. You should just invest in established company's (while you are still learning) or look up common ETFs and see what stocks are in them and try making your own little personal portfolio from that list.  Sure you can get lucky trading but you need to make sure your gains are consistent. I see Meet Kevin commented. I actually stopped watching his videos because he would suggest Robinhood. I can't take people seriously if they are pushing this sort of application to make trades. Still just another person using entertainment to make money but not thinking about the ethics of what they are promoting. If you know anything about trading you would not suggest the worst platform to do so just because that is what people are searching for. Use your platform to educated and teach people not to use Robinhood and why. Anyways, there are a ton of new traders out there today and it will take them a long ass time to learn and a lot of money regardless of the platform. But for those Youtubers out there putting on a tie and acting like they can help you make money and you can clearly see none of the advice has made you money consistently over the year... you may want to rethink who you are getting your advice from. When they say "this is not financial advice" then they start giving you financial advice.... the only reason they would need to do this if they were making money from said advice. These people are polished, have great cameras, enthusiasm, and production quality out the ass hole, but look at other people actually in the field. Many of their videos have terrible sound/video quality, and are sort of boring but give some of the best advice. Keep going back to the drawing board and take entertainment as entertainment. Entertainers need to understand the ethics behind what they are doing. This is sort of like FOX and CNN claiming they are entertainment news to save themselves from legal ramifications on reporting false narratives when they know very well people look to them for actual news. Hold people accountable for their intentions by supporting people that actually add value to your life so that maybe those people can change and post better material that is actually educational and not just entertaining.

I read Tony Robbin’s book “money: master the game” and am trying to model Ray dalio’s approach with 30% stocks, I believe 40% in treasuries, 7.5% gold, 7.5% commodities.

I just started and so I’m just trying to place my money in the best indexes like a vanguard S&p 500 index.
For, as the book says, 96% of professional investors can’t beat the s&p 500. So by buying the market and passively investing, thus getting rid of fees, you’re better than 96%+< investors.

Any little extra money I have I’ll buy individual stocks and what have you. To see where it goes. But I’m not trying to gamble
With that said, as long as robinhood keeps their fees super low, then I’m cool

I encourage everyone to get that book, and at least get the essence or generalities of investing.

Let me translate. Warren Buffet and Charly Monger are saying that Robinhood is bad because it promotes short term trading. You, the pleb, aren't supposed to do that.

You are supposed to work very hard at your job and be sure to obey your boss's every order. If you aren't being payed enough, simply work harder and trust that your boss will generously give you a well deserved raise. In the mean time, these huge institutional investors are totally cool with you taking a few of the pennies you are payed and investing them for the long term. Maybe, when you're sixty five, you can pull that money out and live until you die, but you are not supposed to make short term money in the stock market. Only people like them are supposed to do that.

If you can make short term money in the market, you might get really good at it, and then, you won't need your ownerous job so much, and that spells out problems for the companies that these institutional investors have such large steaks in. If they have to accomodate you, because that's the only way to find workers, they can't control everything you do and demaind that you work whatever hours they want for whatever miniscule pay they are willing to give you.

If you make short term money trading stocks, you might be able to pay yourself, you aren't supposed to have extra money. Only the rich are allowed luxuries. Only people like Warren Buffet are allowed to make their own money and buy what they want. Just shutup and be happy with your allowance, peasant.

textDisplay: Robinhood isn't self-righteous. I think they just saw an angle to get "free" trading to the masses. They still make money. If they really wanted everyone to invest intelligently, they would make you take a tutorial on how investing really works and understanding companies and the fundamentals instead of chasing higher prices and getting rich quick. Which is more detrimental? Having someone put money in a saving account compared to getting wreck in the market and be fearful to invest for a long time then put your money into a saving account; getting wreck will set you back even further especially those trading on margin. I hear it on the streets now when eating a meal when friends talk at another table about losing money trading because they chased the next hot stock and not understanding the financials of a company or anything about the industry the business is in. Looking and hearing the numbers, Robinhood isn't about investing; it's trading which is riskier and has a higher chance of people losing money instead of building wealth.

textDisplay: I mean, yeah, Warren is right, it is all speculation... but, so are all the other avenues to trading stocks.  Aside from the serious analysis that individuals just plain don't have the time for, there is also a lot of stuff that goes on that I would consider insider trading but that somehow isn't considered that.  When Buffet wants to invest in a company he has the opportunity to go and meet the management, to interview the CEO, to examine their supply chains, etc...  stuff that while theoretically possible for others for sure isn't extended to them in practice outside of startups and angel investing sorts of situations.  I guess I could go visit Coke headquarters... but would they let me in?  Would I get to do those interviews?  Of course not, because they don't scale, it isn't feasible for every investor to do this even if the company wanted to, there is only so much time in the day and CEOs supposedly have some sort of real work to do...  So regular people invest blind while Warren is actually in the know.  True, this isn't necessarily knowledge prior to announced earnings or anything like that, which is why it isn't exactly legally insider trading but still seems like unfair practice to me.

textDisplay:
Reminds me of how credit card companies work. They make money from interest, so they set up their business to encourage you to spend more and more so that you can’t pay at the end or make you comfortable with the idea of only paying the monthly payment. They send marketing emails and incentivize you to dine out to get that 0.000001% cash back when otherwise you would have eaten your two-day old pasta at home.

In the case of Robinhood, they set up their app to have investors trade often. Create the atmosphere that you, the investor, is winning.

In both instances of credit card companies and Robinhood, people defend both entities. Arguing that it’s helping them, and that they “are smarter than other people that are bad with money.” That they’re the exception to the rule. Yet again, national debt statistics tell a different story.

textDisplay:
Before Robinhood, I couldn't afford to invest often because all the brokerages had a $5-$8 commission fee per trade. It averaged into your cost per share; so it was only worth buying stock if you were buying expensive stock and/or many shares of the same stock.

I understand people's issues with Robinhood, but I still like to use it. I don't have much in it, but the funds are spread out over many different stocks. The combined total is growing much better than a savings account would.
textOriginal:
Before Robinhood, I couldn't afford to invest often because all the brokerages had a $5-$8 commission fee per trade.  It averaged into your cost per share; so it was only worth buying stock if you were buying expensive stock and/or many shares of the same stock.

I understand people's issues with Robinhood, but I still like to use it.  I don't have much in it, but the funds are spread out over many different stocks.  The combined total is growing much better than a savings account would.

textDisplay:
I'm 67 and when I was about 15 or 16 I did a imaginary stock account and followed the stocks I bought and sold and of course considered fees. I didn't do really bad, although then I would have to wait for my paper share docs to come through the mail or pick up from the broker so there was a lag. Without the lag checking newspaper M-F I did pretty well and grew my account (imaginary acct) by about 10%. Then I saw some news about BIC and Winnebago. The price of Winnebago was under $3 a share and BIC was striking a deal to buy Winnebago. I tried to talk my mother into buying $3k in Winnebago shares because I was convinced the price would at least double. BIC had been growing rapidly with their stick pens. The pens were cheap, seldom skipped like many click ball point pens I've used and every high school I knew of began selling bic pens in the school stores. They were being sold in drug stores and almost anywhere. It was sort of like a revolutionary thing. Okay, back in the late 60's $3k was a lot of money, like new car price and in LA 12-15k would buy a house, nice house. Well, I couldn't convince my mother and maybe she could not have come up with the money anyway. but a month or so later Winnebago price went up to $27 per share.

I guess the moral of the story is I began to learn about investing at a young age, although in my later teens other things took my attention away from investing. I think every person in high school should be taught basic finance. Simple things, like introduction to basic stock market functions and exercises on line with many brokerage firms are free for setting up and following a watch list type account. There you can see how your stocks perform. Simple net worth statements should be taught. How to set a realistic budget and so much more. I know a lot of younger people that cannot, will not, or are afraid to do their own tax returns. That in most cases is silly sad, especially with the apps you can use to figure out your tax disposition and file online. I used to do my own the old fashioned hard way back in the day.

I really think a lot of the issues go back to the education system. However, that doesn't mean that there are not a lot of very intelligent kids or young adults out there that are savvy. For the incident with Robinhood to have happened is a sign all lit up showing their are some regulation clean ups that need to happen. As tech advances, this may be more and more difficult to do, but it needs to get done.

With one good EMP from a solar wind lighting up our digital sky, have you ever thought about how poor you would become overnight? One major solar flare, like what nearly happened in 2012 would wipe out all digital account information. I'm guessing that maybe a fraction of it could be recovered, but over a period of time and again, only a fractional amount could be verified. In this digital age, we have a lot of challenges ahead of us and we need to be maybe a bit more pro-active toward safeguarding and better regulating our digital life. After all, if we are in a virtual reality it will only take a flip of a switch to end us all :) Maybe when our makers turn off the computer and in the morning turn it back on it creates a phenomenon known as Deja vu, ha ha.

textDisplay: Someone once asked me about getting into investing & the stock market. I told them to set up a brokerage account with fidelity, buy SPY, and to stay away from Robinhood as its a gambling app. A few days later they told me about the free stock they got when setting up their Robinhood account. You can lead a horse to water but you can't make it drink. They have no idea how to read financial statements, have never read a book on investing, and have no clue who Warren Buffett is but have been rewarded with a free stock. In my opinion this free stock gimmick can be a crucial step in leading uneducated investors astray.

textDisplay: Sometimes I buy Lego Minifigures. I admit though, I find it frustrating that in shops I go to that sell them they all cost $5. $5 for one tiny Lego minifigure. I like creating my own characters out of various minifigure parts. I recently tried to get a Space Police minifigure but gave up as I felt it was a waste of money and not worth the effort. At least I got ones I wanted such as Barbarian Warrior. Cyborg. Galaxy Trooper. Intergalactic Girl. Gladiator. Female Samurai. Space Bounty Hunter.
